[{"issueId":"015a8dd7-3a7f-4222-9340-c29303eae6b6","aiExplanation":"This text has insufficient color contrast between the foreground text and background colors. The current contrast ratio is 3.5:1, but WCAG AA requires at least 4.5:1 for normal-sized text. This affects users with low vision, color blindness (affecting approximately 8% of men and 0.5% of women), age-related vision changes, or anyone viewing the screen in bright sunlight or on a low-quality display. These users may struggle to read or completely miss this content, which could contain important information.","aiFixSuggestion":"Increase the contrast between the text color and background color to meet the 4.5:1 minimum ratio. You can use tools like the WebAIM Contrast Checker to find compliant color combinations.

Before:
<p class="low-contrast">Sample text with low contrast</p>

After (adjust CSS):
.low-contrast {
  /* Change from low contrast color to higher contrast */
  /* Example: if background is white (#FFFFFF), use darker text */
  color: #595959; /* This gives 7:1 contrast on white */
  /* Or if you need to keep the text color, darken the background */
}

Alternative approaches:
1. Darken the text color while keeping the background
2. Lighten the background while keeping the text color
3. Add a semi-transparent overlay behind the text if it's over an image
4. For large text (18pt+ or 14pt+ bold), the minimum ratio is 3:1, but 4.5:1 is still recommended","aiPriority":8},{"issueId":"967d391c-1ae4-45ca-a926-19316bbb6042","aiExplanation":"This image is missing an alt attribute, which means screen reader users have no way to understand what the image represents. Screen readers may announce the filename 'logo.png' or simply say 'image', providing no meaningful information. If this is a logo or contains important visual information, blind and low-vision users who rely on screen readers will miss this content entirely. This is a direct violation of WCAG Success Criterion 1.1.1, which requires all non-text content to have a text alternative.","aiFixSuggestion":"Add an alt attribute that describes the image's purpose and content. The appropriate alt text depends on the image's function:

Before:
<img src="logo.png">

After (for informative logo):
<img src="logo.png" alt="Company Name Logo">

After (for logo that links to home):
<a href="/"><img src="logo.png" alt="Company Name - Go to homepage"></a>

After (if purely decorative):
<img src="logo.png" alt="">

Note: An empty alt="" is appropriate ONLY for decorative images that add no information. For logos, always provide descriptive text. If the image conveys important information like a chart or infographic, the alt text should summarize the key information or you should provide a longer description via aria-describedby.","aiPriority":9},{"issueId":"453d3c86-c81c-4950-bac4-09a792aecc4f","aiExplanation":"This link contains only an icon with no accessible text, making it impossible for screen reader users to understand where the link leads or what action it performs. When a screen reader encounters this link, it may announce just 'link' with no description, or read out the href '/page' which provides no meaningful context. This creates a significant barrier for blind users who cannot see the icon and need text-based information to navigate the page effectively.","aiFixSuggestion":"Add accessible text to the link using one of these methods:

Before:
<a href="/page"><i class="icon"></i></a>

Option 1 - Add visually hidden text (recommended for icon-only buttons):
<a href="/page">
  <i class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></i>
  <span class="visually-hidden">Go to settings page</span>
</a>

/* CSS for visually hidden class */
.visually-hidden {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px;
  height: 1px;
  padding: 0;
  margin: -1px;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
  white-space: nowrap;
  border: 0;
}

Option 2 - Use aria-label:
<a href="/page" aria-label="Go to settings page">
  <i class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</a>

Option 3 - Add visible text alongside the icon:
<a href="/page">
  <i class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></i>
  Settings
</a>

Note: Adding aria-hidden="true" to the icon element prevents screen readers from attempting to announce the icon itself, which could result in confusing output.","aiPriority":7}]
